{"id":"1903.05105","submitter":"Francesco Belfiore","authors":"F. Belfiore, F. Vincenzo, R. Maiolino, F. Matteucci","title":"From 'bathtub' galaxy evolution models to metallicity gradients","comments":"accepted by MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stz1165","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We model gas phase metallicity radial profiles of galaxies in the local\nUniverse by building on the `bathtub' chemical evolution formalism - where a\ngalaxy's gas content is determined by the interplay between inflow, star\nformation and outflows. In particular, we take into account inside-out disc\ngrowth and add physically-motivated prescriptions for radial gradients in star\nformation efficiency (SFE). We fit analytical models against the metallicity\nradial profiles of low-redshift star-forming galaxies in the mass range\n$\\log(M_\\star/M_\\odot)$ = [9.0-11.0] derived by Belfiore et al. 2017, using\ndata from the MaNGA survey. The models provide excellent fits to the data and\nare capable of reproducing the change in shape of the radial metallicity\nprofiles, including the flattening observed in the centres of massive galaxies.\nWe derive the posterior probability distribution functions for the model\nparameters and find significant degeneracies between them. The parameters\ndescribing the disc assembly timescale are not strongly constrained from the\nmetallicity profiles, while useful constrains are obtained for the SFE (and its\nradial dependence) and the outflow loading factor. The inferred value for the\nSFE is in good agreement with observational determinations. The inferred\noutflow loading factor is found to decrease with stellar mass, going from\nnearly unity at $\\log(M_\\star/M_\\odot) = 9.0$ to close to zero at\n$\\log(M_\\star/M_\\odot) =11.0$, in general agreement with previous empirical\ndeterminations. These values are the lowest we can obtain for a\nphysically-motivated choice of initial mass function and metallicity\ncalibration. We explore alternative choices which produce larger loading\nfactors at all masses, up to order unity at the high-mass end.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Mar 2019 18:00:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 26 Apr 2019 14:43:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-15"}
{"id":"1903.05106","submitter":"Emma Beasor Ms.","authors":"Emma R. Beasor, Ben Davies, Nathan Smith and Nate Bastian","title":"Discrepancies in the ages of young star clusters; evidence for mergers?","comments":"Accepted for publication in MNRAS. 9 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stz732","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  There is growing evidence that star clusters can no longer be considered\nsimple stellar populations (SSPs). Intermediate and old age clusters are often\nfound to have extended main sequence turn-offs (eMSTOs) which are difficult to\nexplain with single age isochrones, an effect attributed to rotation. In this\npaper, we provide the first characterisation of this effect in young (<20Myr)\nclusters. We determine ages for 4 young massive clusters (2 LMC, 2 Galactic) by\nthree different methods: using the brightest single turn-off (TO) star; using\nthe luminosity function (LF) of the TO; and by using the lowest $L_{\\rm bol}$\nred supergiant (RSG). The age found using the cluster TO is consistently\nyounger than the age found using the lowest RSG $L_{\\rm bol}$. Under the\nassumption that the lowest luminosity RSG age is the `true' age, we argue that\nthe eMSTOs of these clusters cannot be explained solely by rotation or\nunresolved binaries. We speculate that the most luminous stars above the TO are\nmassive blue straggler stars formed via binary interaction, either as mass\ngainers or merger products. Therefore, using the cluster TO method to infer\nages and initial masses of post-main sequence stars such as Wolf-Rayet stars,\nluminous blue variables and RSGs, will result in ages inferred being too young\nand masses too high.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Mar 2019 18:00:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-10"}
