{"id":"1903.05348","submitter":"Young S Kim","authors":"Sibel Baskal, Young S. Kim, and Marilyn E. Noz","title":"Poincar\\'e Symmetry from Heisenberg's Uncertainty Relations","comments":"10 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":"Symmetry, vol.11, pages 49:1-9 (2019)","doi":"10.3390/sym11030409","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is noted that the single-variable Heisenberg commutation relation contains\nthe symmetry of the $Sp(2)$ group which is isomorphic to the Lorentz group\napplicable to one time-like dimension and two space-like dimensions, known as\nthe $O(2,1)$ group. According to Paul A. M. Dirac, from the uncertainty\ncommutation relations for two variables, it possible to construct the de Sitter\ngroup $O(3,2)$, namely the Lorentz group applicable to three space-like\nvariables and two time-like variables. By contracting one of the time-like\nvariables in $O(3,2)$, it is possible, to construct the inhomogeneous Lorentz\ngroup $IO(3,1)$ which serves as the fundamental symmetry group for quantum\nmechanics and quantum field theory in the Lorentz covariant world. This\n$IO(3,1)$ group is commonly known as the Poincar\\'e group.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 Mar 2019 07:56:54 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 21 Mar 2019 03:17:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-22"}
