{"id":"1903.05373","submitter":"Gemma De las Cuevas","authors":"Gemma De las Cuevas, Tom Drescher, Tim Netzer","title":"Separability for mixed states with operator Schmidt rank two","comments":"12 pages. v2: We thank A. Mueller-Hermes, M. Studinski and N.\n  Johnston for pointing out to us that the first main result of this paper (our\n  Theorem 1) had been first proven by D. Cariello using other techniques. We\n  have updated our manuscript accordingly, have changed the title, and slightly\n  modified the abstract. v3: minor changes. Accepted for publication in\n  Quantum. v4: modified license","journal-ref":"Quantum 3, 203 (2019)","doi":"10.22331/q-2019-12-02-203","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph math-ph math.MP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The operator Schmidt rank is the minimum number of terms required to express\na state as a sum of elementary tensor factors. Here we provide a new proof of\nthe fact that any bipartite mixed state with operator Schmidt rank two is\nseparable, and can be written as a sum of two positive semidefinite matrices\nper site. Our proof uses results from the theory of free spectrahedra and\noperator systems, and illustrates the use of a connection between\ndecompositions of quantum states and decompositions of nonnegative matrices. In\nthe multipartite case, we prove that any Hermitian Matrix Product Density\nOperator (MPDO) of bond dimension two is separable, and can be written as a sum\nof at most four positive semidefinite matrices per site. This implies that\nthese states can only contain classical correlations, and very few of them. In\ncontrast, MPDOs of bond dimension three can contain an unbounded amount of\nclassical correlations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 Mar 2019 09:25:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 21 Mar 2019 08:27:09 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 2 Nov 2019 07:48:24 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Mon, 11 Nov 2019 15:03:31 GMT"}],"u